pass.isabelle TODO
==================

[BUG] Get_mask(a, -1) all-ones mask is emitted at the mask pin's 1-bit width
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

Status:   RESOLVED
  - pass.isabelle: fixed upstream by "pass.isabelle: preserve Get_mask and Sext
    widths" (origin/fix/isabelle-get-mask-sext-width, cherry-picked as
    cb636f4ca). The mask is now materialized at the source width, so the -1
    sentinel becomes all-ones over every source bit (Get_mask(a,-1) == zext a).
  - pass.lean: fixed in pass/lean/pass_lean.cpp Get_mask emit + certificate
    mask-dep, widened to max(src_w, out_w) (behaviorally identical to the
    src_w widening; the source has no bits above src_w).
  Both validated by the add2 oracle:
    forall a b : BitVec 4, add2_comb {a,b}.out_y = a + b   (and = add2_comb_cert).

Found:    2026 (Lean port add2 oracle check)
Severity: HIGH — produced semantically wrong models for the canonical zext idiom
Present since: 590f019d5 "Add Isabelle graph export pass" (2026-06-05).
              This was NOT a regression; the all-ones mask sentinel was never
              handled until the fix above.

Symptom
-------
LiveHD's canonical zero-extend idiom lowers to `Get_mask(x, mask=-1)`, which per
pass/cprop/cprop.cpp:852 means `get_mask(a,-1) == a` (take ALL bits of x, zero
extended). The `-1` is an all-ones sentinel of conceptually infinite width.

Both the fast model and the certificate materialize the mask at the mask PIN's
declared width, which the front-end sets to 1 for a `-1` constant:

    uint32_t mask_w = pin_width(ctx, mask, node);          // == 1
    ... sem_get_mask (ucast a :: src word) (ucast mask :: 1 word) ...

`word_of_int (-1) :: 1 word` = `1`, so `mask_indices` of a 1-bit `1` is `[0]`,
and `sem_get_mask a 1` collapses to *bit 0 of a* instead of the full value.

Concrete failure (add2.sv = `y = a + b`, 4-bit):
    a=5, b=3  -> emitted model yields y=2  (bit0(5)+bit0(3) = 1+1 = 2)
                 correct RTL value is y=8.

Why it still typechecks / proves
--------------------------------
The fast model AND the certificate evaluator share the identical 1-bit mask, so
`<top>_comb = <top>_comb_cert` and `<top>_evalGraph_correct` both hold. The
translation contract "model = certificate" is satisfied; only "model = RTL" is
violated — which the LEC frontend gate is responsible for catching.

Fix (apply to BOTH the fast-model emit and the cert mask-dep, in lockstep so the
bridge theorem keeps holding)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
The disambiguation must happen at emission time, while the mask is still a Dlop
and known to be `-1` / all-ones (`v.same_repr(Dlop::create_integer(-1))` or
`get_mask_range()` covering all source bits). Materialize the mask at
`max(src_w, out_w)` instead of the mask pin's 1-bit width:

  - `-1`  -> all-ones over the source width  -> selects every source bit = zext.
  - a concrete non-negative pattern -> high bits pad with 0 (no behavior change).

This matches cgen_sim.cpp:201 `a.get_mask_op(mask).zext_to<tw>`.

Reference fix already applied in pass/lean/pass_lean.cpp (Ntype_op::Get_mask):

    const uint32_t mask_src_w = pin_width(ctx, drivers[0], node);
    const uint32_t mask_w     = std::max(mask_src_w, w);
    ... sem_get_mask <a> (mask materialized at mask_w) ...

The same widening must be applied to the certificate's mask dependency so the
cert const node carries the widened all-ones value (mask consts are dedicated
per Get_mask in practice, so widening the const width is safe).

Validation
----------
Add an oracle check (not just a typecheck/lake/isabelle-build smoke test) for a
design whose Get_mask(-1) feeds arithmetic, e.g. add2: assert
`add2_comb {a:=5, b:=3} = {y:=8}` and a wrap case `{a:=10,b:=10} = {y:=4}`.
